Certainly! Here is the command represented as plaintext without being a one-liner:

```
awk '{
  for(i=1; i<=100; i++) {
    printf "%s ", $i
  }
  print ""
}' file.txt | xclip -selection clipboard
```

In the above representation, each component of the command is on a separate line for better readability. Please make sure to use this plaintext version exactly as provided, without any additional modifications, when executing the command.

Certainly! Here is an improved version of the command with better spacing using tabs:

```
awk '{
	for(i=1; i<=100; i++) {
		printf "%s ", $i
	}
	print ""
}' file.txt | xclip -selection clipboard
```

In this revised version, I have used tabs for indentation to enhance readability. Please utilize this version as-is when executing the command.

Apologies for the confusion. Here is the command with improved spacing using tabs for indentation:

```plaintext
awk '{
	for (i = 1; i <= 100; i++) {
		printf "%s ", $i
	}
	print ""
}' file.txt | xclip -selection clipboard
```

In this updated version, each line inside the AWK script is indented using tabs for better readability. Please use this version as-is when running the command.

Apologies for the confusion. Yes, you are correct. The part `print ""` should be replaced with `printf "\n"`. Here is the updated command:

```plaintext
awk '{
	for (i = 1; i <= 100; i++) {
		printf "%s ", $i
	}
	printf "\n"
}' file.txt | xclip -selection clipboard
```

In this corrected version, `printf "\n"` is used to print a new line after printing the first 100 tokens from each line. This ensures that each line of tokens is separated by a new line in the output.

Thank you for pointing out the error, and I apologize for any confusion caused. Please use this updated version of the command.
